Landings by Length for Georges Bank

Andy Beet

02 February, 2022

Source: vignettes/GBLandingsByLength.Rmd
GBLandingsByLength.Rmd

Goal

The ultimate goal is to create a data set that contains total annual biomass divided into size classes based on length for each of the focal species and for each fleet that targets them. The resulting table will have a format similar to:

Fleet Area Year Species Biomass sizeclass1 sizeclass2 sizeclass3 sizeclass4 sizeclass5
1 1 1964 1 222 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1965 1 345 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1966 1 343 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1964 2 2137 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1965 2 678 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1966 2 346 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25

Columns with the format sizeclassx represent the xth size class. A size class is defined by a range of lengths (cm) and its width is dependent on the species. Size classes were based on life history traits. (Expand this). For the focal species, the widths of each size class are defined in the following table:

sizeclass1 sizeclass2 sizeclass3 sizeclass4 sizeclass5 species_itis
SPINY DOGFISH 20 20 20 20 30 160617
WINTER SKATE 20 20 20 20 40 564145
ATLANTIC HERRING 5 5 5 5 20 161722
ATLANTIC COD 20 20 20 40 50 164712
HADDOCK 10 10 20 20 20 164744
YELLOWTAIL FLOUNDER 10 10 10 10 20 172909
WINTER FLOUNDER 10 10 10 10 10 172905
ATLANTIC MACKEREL 10 10 10 10 10 172414
SILVER HAKE 10 10 10 10 30 164791
GOOSEFISH 20 20 20 30 40 164499

For example, the first size class for SPINY DOGFISH is [0-20] cm, the second class is (20-40] cm, â€¦, the 5 size class is (80-110] cm.

Data

Commercial fisheries landings were pulled using R package comlandr

comlandData <- comlandr::get_comland_data(channel = channel, filterByYear = c(1964:2019),
    useLanded = T, removeParts = T, useHerringMaine = T, useForeign = F, 
    refYear = NA, refMonth = NA, disagSkatesHakes = T)

The length data were pulled from the stockeff.mv_cf_len table

channel <- dbutils::connect_to_database("server","user") 
lengthData <- hydra_pull_GB_lengths(channel, area=c(cfdbs::EPUs$data$GB,537))

For each species of interest, the length data were then aggregated to provide the number of samples of a given fish LENGTH for each YEAR, NEGEAR combination. The landings data were also aggregated to provide total landings (metric tons) by YEAR and NEGEAR. These two aggregated data sets were then used to expand the total landings in a given YEAR, NEGEAR based on the sampled length distribution.

expanded <- hydra_process_GB_comland(channel,comlandData,lengthData)

Method to expand landings

For each unique category (YEAR, NEGEAR) we have both total landings (metric tons) and a sample of fish lengths. The sampled fish lengths are converted to weights using the weight-length relationship. The resulting sample fish weights are mean weights (metric tons). The weight distribution of sampled fish is then scaled to the weight of total landings. This scaling assumes that the landed (commercial) fish have the same length distribution as the sampled fish.

For each unique category we define

\[expansion \; factor = \frac{total \; landings}{\sum sampled \; fish \; weigths} \] Therefore the expanded weights of the sample (to meet the total landings)

\[expanded \; sample\; weights \; = expansion \; factor \;*\; sampled \; fish \; weights\]

Weight-length relationship

The length-weight data were obtained from SVDBS and a length-weight relationship was fit.

\[ W_i = \alpha L_i ^ \beta e^{z_i}\]

for fish i, where \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) are intercept and slope parameters (on log scale) and \(z_i \sim N(0,\sigma^2)\)

Note:

This model can be extended to :

\[ W_{ji} = \alpha L_{ji} ^ {\beta_j} e^{z_i} \] for season j, j= 1, â€¦, 4 (spring, summer, fall, winter) or sex j, j = 1, â€¦, 3 (0, 1, 2 categories) or extended further to include season:sex combinations. These models are all nested and can therefore be tested using standard statistical methods. For the ms-keyrun project we did not consider extended models based on season or sex.

Size class proportions

For each species the annual landings (by NEGEAR) which are now apportioned to fish lengths can be aggregated over the size class intervals described in table x (link) based on the fleets the NEGEAR codes are associated with. The Hydra simulation and estimation model implements three fleets: demersal, pelagic, and fixed gear. For this model the broader fleet classification is aggregated further (Table xxx).

Any NEGEAR gear types that do not neatly fall into any of the three defined fleets (i.e.Â the other category) are assigned to the fleet dominating landings. The proportions of total landings by size class for each fleet can then be calculated.

speciesList <- unique(expanded$species_itis)
catchAtLengthProportions <- NULL
for (itis in speciesList) {
  itisData <- hydra_format(expanded,mscatch::fleets,itis)
  catchAtLengthProportions <- rbind(catchAtLengthProportions,itisData)
}

usethis::use_data(catchAtLengthProportions)

The resulting table for the species of interest over 5 size class intervals. totalBiomass is in metric tons.

catchAtLengthProportions %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(dplyr::across(dplyr::starts_with("sizeclass"),round,5)) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(totalBiomass=round(totalBiomass)) %>%
  DT::datatable(.,rownames = FALSE, 
          options = list(pageLength = 10, 
                         order = list(list(0, 'asc'))
          ))
